  <!-- Best-fit parameters of the halo mass function model of Benson et al. (2026;                                            -->
  <!-- https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2026arXiv260612137B), as used by the halo mass function validation models.           -->
  <!--                                                                                                                        -->
  <!-- Note that the calibration of this model was performed using the original parameterization of the `artificialHalos`     -->
  <!-- cosmological mass variance class, in which the artificial variance was                                                 -->
  <!--   S_artificial = S_0 (M/M_0)^alpha D^2(t),   with M_0 = artificialCountParticles * massParticle.                       -->
  <!-- The current parameterization has no normalization S_0 (it is degenerate with M_0), i.e.                                -->
  <!--   S_artificial = (M/M_0)^alphaM D^2beta(t).                                                                            -->
  <!-- The best-fit values (artificialCountParticles=3.91472212965412, artificialNormalization=2.99326650103751,              -->
  <!-- artificialExponent=-0.606650168611276) are therefore mapped to the current parameterization via                        -->
  <!--   artificialCountParticles   -> 3.91472212965412 * 2.99326650103751^(-1/-0.606650168611276) = 23.854884384745247,      -->
  <!--   artificialExponentMass     -> artificialExponent,                                                                     -->
  <!--   artificialExponentGrowthFactor -> 1 (fixed in the original parameterization),                                        -->
  <!-- which yields an identical artificial variance.                                                                         -->

